  var DIV = {"1": [{"range": "Genesis 1:26; Genesis 17:6; 2 Samuel 7:16; Mark 1:14-15; Revelation 11:15", "title": "The story of God's Kingdom", "questions": [], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 3:17-19; Exodus 19:4-6; Matthew 1:21; Revelation 21:3-4", "title": "The Story of God’s Salvation", "questions": [], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 3:15; Genesis 17:1-2; Jeremiah 31:31-32; Mark 14:24-25", "title": "The Story of God’s Promises", "questions": [], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}], "2": [{"range": "Genesis 1:1-2:3", "title": "The first creation account", "questions": [{"prompt": "Look at how God creates — what pattern do you see across the six days?", "hint": "Notice the rhythm: 'And God said… and it was so… and God saw that it was good.'", "answer": "God creates by His word, in ordered stages, declaring each good. The pattern reveals a deliberate, ordering Creator — not random emergence."}, {"prompt": "Who or what does God set 'over' creation on day 6, and why does that matter?", "hint": "Re-read Genesis 1:26-28. Note the verbs 'image', 'rule', 'subdue'.", "answer": "Man — made in God's image — is given dominion. This is the kingdom pattern: God rules over Man; Man, as image-bearer, has dominion over creation."}, {"prompt": "What does the seventh day add to the pattern?", "hint": "Look at Genesis 2:1-3 carefully — what does God do, and what does He call this day?", "answer": "God rests and sanctifies the seventh day. Creation isn't just orderly — it culminates in rest and blessing. The kingdom is meant to be enjoyed, not just maintained."}], "summary": "Genesis 1 sets the pattern: God's people, under God's good rule, in God's blessing — with Man given dominion over creation. This is the kingdom ideal that the rest of the OT will measure everything against.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 2:4-25", "title": "Account of creation of Man", "questions": [{"prompt": "How is the creation of Man described differently here than in Genesis 1?", "hint": "Notice the verbs — 'formed', 'breathed', 'put', 'took'. What's the tone?", "answer": "It's intimate and personal — God forms Man from dust and breathes life into him. Man isn't just spoken into being; he is shaped by God's own hand."}, {"prompt": "What is Man's vocation in the garden (Gen 2:15)?", "hint": "The Hebrew verbs here ('abad' and 'shamar') are also used of priestly service in the Tabernacle.", "answer": "To 'work it and keep it' — language used later for priests in the Tabernacle. Man is a kind of priest in God's first sanctuary, the garden."}, {"prompt": "Why does God make a woman, and what does that say about the human design?", "hint": "Re-read Genesis 2:18-25. Note 'not good' — the first time anything in creation is called 'not good'.", "answer": "Man alone is 'not good'. Humans are made for covenantal partnership — to image God together, not in isolation."}], "summary": "Genesis 2 zooms in: God's people are formed intimately, given priestly vocation, and made for covenantal relationship. God is the life-giver.", "summaryHint": ""}], "3": [{"range": "Genesis 3:1-6", "title": "The Fall", "questions": [{"prompt": "How exactly do Adam & Eve go wrong?", "hint": "Describe what's going on in their hearts.", "answer": ""}, {"prompt": "Come up with a definition of sin from these first few verses.", "hint": "Think about God's perfect created kingdom order versus what's happening now.", "answer": "Sin is rebellion against God's perfect order: seeking to be God ourselves."}], "summary": "Sin is rebellion against God's perfect order: seeking to be God ourselves.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 3:7-20", "title": "The Consequences of the Fall", "questions": [{"prompt": "What are the immediate consequences of the fall?", "hint": "Compare Genesis 3:7 and 2:25.", "answer": "Immediate consequences: A broken relationship with God, each other and creation. Compare Genesis 2:25 with Genesis 3:7."}, {"prompt": "What are the various curses which God mentions?", "hint": "Look at v14-v19 and sort according to Serpent, woman and man.", "answer": "Curse to the serpent: Cursed above all livestock, enmity between it and woman. Its offspring's head shall be bruised by the woman's offspring; while its offspring will bruise the woman's offspring's head. (IMPORTANT)\nCurse to the woman: God multiplies pain in childbearing, desire shall be against husband while he shall rule over you (Desires against God's kingdom order)\nCurse to the man: Cursed is the ground because of man, in pain/sweat shall he eat from his labour all the days of his life. DEATH - As he, as dust, is taken from the ground; to dust shall he return."}], "summary": "The consequences of man's sin implicate the whole of creation as pain and death follow. However, God promises redemption through the \"woman's offspring\".", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 3:20-24", "title": "The Aftermath of the Fall", "questions": [{"prompt": "What has been added to the consequences as a result of Adam and Eve's actions?", "hint": "Look at verses 21 and 24.", "answer": "The very first instance of blood sacrifice for sin - animals were killed to clothe Adam and Eve (v21).\nThey were kicked out of the Garden of Eden (v24)."}, {"prompt": "What hope is there after the fall?", "hint": "Look at Genesis 3:15 and 3:21", "answer": "The serpent's offspring's death is foretold through the woman's offspring in Genesis 3:15 ; God himself still clothes Adam and Eve in Genesis 3:21."}], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}], "4": [{"range": "Genesis 6:5-22", "title": "The Worldwide Problem", "questions": [{"prompt": "What strikes you about sin and humanity? How do you personally feel and think about what you see?", "hint": "Extent/Depth/Effects of sin?", "answer": "Extent of sin : All humans ; \nDepths of sin : Our hearts, continually ; \nEffects of sin: Violence/corruption."}, {"prompt": "What do we hear about how the LORD feels towards all that He’s created? What comes to mind as you see the words describing God’s response?", "hint": "", "answer": "How the LORD feels: “regret” / “sorry” (same word in Hebrew); “How can God not feel grief and sorrow at the broken and sinful creation He lovingly made?”"}, {"prompt": "Read Genesis 5:28-29. What does Noah's name mean? Consider whether he lives up to his name throughout the study.", "hint": "", "answer": "Noah means \"rest\"; He would bring \"relief\" from the painful toil of working the ground that God cursed. This is done through... his \"righteous\"ness."}], "summary": "God is grieved by sin, which is shown to deeply affect every human's hearts, causing violence.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 7", "title": "The Flood Judgment", "questions": [{"prompt": "What is it about Noah that is “righteous”?", "hint": "Genesis 6:8-9, 6:22, 7:5, 7:8-9, 7:15-16.", "answer": "Noah found favour in the eyes of God, and obeyed God consistently."}, {"prompt": "What was the impact of Noah's obedience?", "hint": "See Genesis 8:1.", "answer": "One man's obedience led to God remembering Noah and all the beasts and all the livestock in the ark (Genesis 8:1)."}, {"prompt": "Look at the language used in the Flood's destruction and compare it with the creation accounts in Genesis 1-2. How would you describe what the flood has done? Click show hint for the passages.", "hint": "Compare Genesis 7:19 to Genesis 1:9-10. \nCompare Genesis 2:7 to Genesis 7:22.", "answer": "The flood covered the whole earth, including the high mountains, undoing God's separation of dry land and waters in Genesis 1:9-10. \nThe flood killed everything with the breath of life, life which God breathes, especially given to man (Genesis 2:7)."}], "summary": "God started to restore creation through one favoured man, Noah, who was righteous and obeyed God.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 8-9", "title": "The Covenant", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Genesis 8:15-19 and 9:1-3. What does this language remind you of in the earlier OT narrative? Why are we being reminded of this?", "hint": "Recall the Creation account in Genesis 1:22;28.", "answer": "Language from the creation narrative - \"Be fruitful and multiply\". Pointing towards a reversal of the curse, towards Eden..?"}, {"prompt": "Read Genesis 8:20-22 and then 9:8-17. What exactly is God promising Noah and his family? How do you think and feel about these promises?", "hint": "What does God say about man's heart? What is the covenant God makes with Noah and his family and creation?", "answer": "God recognises man's heart is evil from youth. Still, God promises never again to wipe out all flesh with a flood."}, {"prompt": "Read Genesis 9:18-29. What happens to Noah and his family after the flood?", "hint": "Language of Leviticus: “uncover nakedness” suggests  sexual immorality (Lev. 18, 20).", "answer": "The sinfulness of mankind is apparent, from Noah's drunkenness to Ham's immorality; More curses arrive as a result."}], "summary": "Man (and our hearts) is the heart of the sin problem. The worldwide ‘washing’ doesn’t return the world to Eden. Yet\nGod is committed to His promises to Adam - To renew His entire creation.", "summaryHint": ""}], "5": [{"range": "Genesis 12:1-9; 15:1-6; 15:18-21; 17:1-14", "title": "The promises of the Covenant", "questions": [{"prompt": "Build the picture of the Abrahamic Promises in Gen 12, 15 & 17.", "hint": "Look for common themes based on what God promises, Genesis 15 and 17 build upon Genesis 12.", "answer": "God promises land, descendents and blessings to Abraham, and a relationship with Him."}, {"prompt": "Recall any similarities in language between what God promises Abraham and Genesis 1-3?", "hint": "Any common words like \"Fruitful\", common themes of dominion?", "answer": "Both passages contain themes of being fruitful (in descendants), right order/dominion (Genesis 17:6); with the land promised in Genesis 15:19-20 being partially similar to the rivers in Eden."}], "summary": "God makes a covenant with Abraham, promising to reverse the curse to a certain degree through him.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 15:8-21", "title": "The Sealing of the Covenant", "questions": [{"prompt": "Who is this smoking fire and flaming torch? (c.f. Exodus 13:21-22)", "hint": "Context: Moses wrote the Torah (First 5 books of the Bible), and readers of Genesis will have been through/known about the events up till Deuteronomy, before they entered the Promised Land, including Exodus 13:21-22.", "answer": "From how God appeared in Exodus, leading the Israelites at the Red Sea and at the Tabernacle, God can be safely said to be represented by the flaming torch and the thick smoke."}, {"prompt": "Read Jer 34:18-20. How does it help us understand the significance of this ritual?", "hint": "Notice what will happen to the people who passed between the pieces but break the covenant.", "answer": "God alone, himself, is passing through the pieces, guaranteeing with His life, that He will keep His part of the covenant."}], "summary": "God alone, himself, through the ritual in Genesis 15:8-21, guarantees He will keep the covenant made to Abraham.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Genesis 15:6; 17:1; 17:22", "title": "Abraham's Faith & Obedience", "questions": [{"prompt": "What is Abraham's key, initial response to God in Genesis 15:6?", "hint": "", "answer": "Abraham believed God, and it was counted to him as righteousness."}, {"prompt": "Where else do you find Abraham's expected response to God in Gen 17?", "hint": "Gen 17:1.", "answer": "Abram is expected to walk before God and be blameless (righteous). Abraham later demonstrates obedience and faith in God through the sacrifice of Isaac (Genesis 22:12)."}], "summary": "The response of Abraham to God's covenant was faith expressed in obedience.", "summaryHint": ""}], "6": [{"range": "Exodus 11", "title": "10th Plague threatened", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 11:7. What has the LORD been showing through the 9 plagues so far?", "hint": "For additional context, reference 5:2 // 6:3 // 6:7 // 7:45 if needed.", "answer": "The LORD has shown He is most powerful - above Pharoah and his magicians/deities. God clearly makes a distinction between Egypt and Israel."}, {"prompt": "Based on Exodus 11:3, how is Moses viewed now?", "hint": "", "answer": "Moses was \"very great\" in the land of Egypt, even in the sight of Pharoah's servants and people."}, {"prompt": "Read Exodus 11:4-10. What is Pharoah's response and why does he respond in this way?", "hint": "Context: \"Harden\" may also mean \"Strengthen\". In the early plagues, Pharoah hardens his own heart; in later plagues, God does 11:10. The purpose of which, being mentioned in v9.", "answer": "Pharoah hardens/strengthens his heart continually, as God also hardens pharoah's heart. The result is Pharoah not listening. God did so in order that His wonders may be multiplied in the land of  Egypt."}], "summary": "God’s salvation (of Israel) goes hand-in-hand with God’s judgment (of Egypt), to show God makes a distinction between Israel and Egypt.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 12", "title": "Passover", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 12:1-5; 14. What is so significant about the Passover, even for future generations? (Read the rest of Exodus 12 for additional immersion).", "hint": "Notice the timing and scale of the Passover.", "answer": "The Passover redefines their calendar - it begins their year and life as a nation (A new beginning!). Everyone has to participate and remember this \"forever\". The sheer scale of the event in lambs slaughtered and roasted at the same time also makes it that much more memorable/impactful.\nThe message it conveys is clear- a sacrifice is killed to save another."}], "summary": "God’s salvation (of Israel) goes hand-in-hand with God’s judgment (of Egypt). This great deliverance redefines the Israelite's lives, and is to be remembered and commemorated regularly forever.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 13", "title": "Consecration of the Firstborn", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Ex. 13:1-2; 11-16. What does the LORD say about the firstborn?", "hint": "\"Redeeming\" with a lamb means killing a lamb in its place.", "answer": "All the firstborn should be consecrated to God - they are His. Additionally all firstborn of man shall be redeemed through the sacrifice of a lamb."}, {"prompt": "Read Exodus 13:13-16. Why does He say these things and require these of all firstborn?", "hint": "Note the purpose and effect of redeeming/consecrating the firstborns.", "answer": "That in time, their children (and all Israel) will know God brought them out of Egypt by a strong hand."}, {"prompt": "What does all this show us about the relationship between newly/about-to-be-rescued Israel and Yahweh?", "hint": "What does God really want Israel to remember through the Passover/Firstborn?", "answer": "The lesson for every generation – God’s Salvation thru God’s judgment (13:14-15)"}], "summary": "God’s salvation (of Israel) goes hand-in-hand with God’s judgment (of Egypt). This great deliverance is to be remembered and commemorated regularly forever, through the treatment of the firstborn.", "summaryHint": ""}], "7": [{"range": "Exodus 19:1-8", "title": "The Mosaic Covenant Proposed", "questions": [{"prompt": "Exodus 19:4-6 is a key moment- the Mosaic Covenant proposed. \n1. Basis of the covenant- What has God done for Israel so far? See Exodus 19:4.", "hint": "Exodus 19:4", "answer": "God saved Israel through judgement of the Egyptians, bringing them to Himself powerfully."}, {"prompt": "2.Response required; What response is required from the people? How is this different from the Abrahamic Covenant?", "hint": "Exodus 19:5; Recall Genesis 15:8-21..", "answer": "In Exodus 19:5, obeying God's voice is required, though it is the pattern since Noah's time. In Genesis 15, God alone guaranteed the covenant himself."}, {"prompt": "3. What would be Israel's new purpose under the covenant?", "hint": "Exodus 19:6 - 3 parts.", "answer": "Treasured possession among all the earth; God's kingdom of priests ; God's holy nation (as He is holy - distinct)."}], "summary": "After delivering Israel mightily, God invites Israel to enter into a blessed covenantal relationship with Him,  which requires their obedience.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 19:9-25", "title": "Israel's distance & fear", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 19:9-25. What are God's instructions regarding approaching the mountain?", "hint": "Notice the internal and external distance between Israel and  God.", "answer": "Israel must consecrate themselves (but still unable to go up the mountain), and cannot touch the mountain (v12-13, 21-25) lest they die. Thunderbolts and lightning cause Israel to tremble and fear."}, {"prompt": "What does this show about God and Israel's relationship with Him?", "hint": "", "answer": "God is holy; Israel is sinful. Israel is far from what they should be under God's good covenant in Exodus 19:4-6…"}], "summary": "Although God establishes a covenantal relationship with Israel, the distance between holy God and sinful, fearful Israel is great.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 20:1-17", "title": "The Covenant Obligations", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 20:1-17. How do God's commandments reflect Israel's purpose in Exodus 19:4-6?", "hint": "Think of how Israel should be under this covenant - \"Treasured Possession\", \"Holy Nation\". How do the commandments align with these?", "answer": "Relationship with God alone, Set apart (from other nations) in treating one another, in all of life. Note 20:17 - which prohibits coveting - a HEART issue."}, {"prompt": "How are Israel's chances to obey (uphold their part of the covenant?)", "hint": "See Exodus 20:17; Consider Israel's repeated grumblings right after being delivered from Egypt.", "answer": "Israel's track record of grumblings, in addition to the extremely difficult commandment of not coveting (controlling their thoughts) meant their chances were almost zero."}], "summary": "God's commandments are aimed at establishing Israel as His covenantal, holy people. Yet sinful, fearful Israel seems highly unlikely to obey.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 20:18-21", "title": "The Covenant Mediator", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 20:18-21. Knowing Israel's state, what is Moses' role and how important is he?", "hint": "In Chap 19 alone, Moses goes up and down thrice; see Exodus 20:21 too.", "answer": "They need a mediator Moses, the only one able to draw near to God (20:21),to stand between them and God, so that they can hear God’s words and\nobey him and keep his covenant."}], "summary": "Hence, the mediator, Moses, is crucial in mediating the relationship between Holy God and sinful Israel. More will be seen regarding mediators in future sessions.", "summaryHint": ""}], "8": [{"range": "Exodus 24:1-11", "title": "The Mosaic Covenant Sealed", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 24:1-11. What has changed in how the people of Israel related to God since Exodus 20?", "hint": "Recall Exodus 20's image of a fearful Israel, where only Moses could go up the mountain to God.", "answer": "Now, Aaron, Nadab and Abihu and 70 elders of Israel are able to come up the mountain partially and worship God from afar. Furthermore, they \"beheld\" God, and \"ate and drank\"."}, {"prompt": "Read Exodus 24:3-11. What did Moses do which improved the relationship between Israel and God?", "hint": "Note all the different steps from 24:3-8.", "answer": "Moses told the people all God's words and rules while the people agreed. He built an altar with 12 pillars, led the people in offering burnt and peace offerings to God, threw half of the blood against the altar, read the Book of the Covenant (written words of the Lord), got Israel's full agreement, then threw the blood on the people."}], "summary": "Mediator Moses plays a crucial role in advancing the Mosaic covenant through rituals, allowing Israel to enjoy a closer relationship with God.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 24:12-25:40", "title": "Instructions for the Tabernacle", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 25:1-9. What is the purpose of this God-given design of the Tabernacle?", "hint": "Exodus 25:2 & 8.", "answer": "God intended to dwell in their midst; and for Israel to FREELY contribute to the building of the tabernacle from their HEARTS."}, {"prompt": "What is the siginificance of God dwelling in their midst through the Tabernacle? (Especially knowing Israel still needs to journey to the promised land)", "hint": "Does God need to remain on Mt Sinai while the people travel to the promised land?", "answer": "The tabernacle is like a 'mobile' Mt Sinai since God can dwell in their midst."}, {"prompt": "Hence, compare the design of the Tabernacle with Mt Sinai to see how God intends to relate to Israel. In addition, note the Tabernacle elements which seem representative of Eden (Exodus 26:1 // Genesis 3:24; Exodus 25:31-32  // Tree of life in Eden)\n(DIFFICULT Question- Click hint for attached helping image)", "hint": "(*Attach Mt sinai vs tabernacle image here*)", "answer": "The structure of the Tabernacle seem to match that of Mt Sinai. Hints of Eden can be seen from the cherubim on the curtains and the tree-like lampstand possibly symbolising the tree-of-life.", "__IMG__": "imgSinaiVsTabernacle", "imageAlt": "Mt Sinai vs Tabernacle — visual comparison"}], "summary": "Through the design of the tabernacle, God intends to dwell with Israel even on the move, progressing towards establishing His perfect kingdom order in Eden.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 31:12-18", "title": "Sabbath — The Covenant Sign", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 31:12-18. What is so significant about the Sabbath, that it should be kept \"Above all\"?", "hint": "See Exodus 31:13 &17 for the Sabbath's origin and what it signifies.", "answer": "The Sabbath, which is God's created, perfect design, is kept as a sign that God is the one who sanctifies Israel. This points towards some restoration towards God's perfect kingdom order in Eden too."}], "summary": "Through requiring Israel to keep the Sabbath, God is shown to sanctify His people, and intends to make progress towards establishing His perfect kingdom order in Eden.", "summaryHint": ""}], "9": [{"range": "Exodus 32", "title": "The Sin of Israel", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 32:1-10; 19; 25. God wants to wipe Israel (except for Moses) out. Why is God so angry with them?", "hint": "Recall the purpose of the gold in Ex 25; and the commandments in Ex 20.", "answer": "The people broke the first 2 commandments, used the gold to worship an idol instead of building the tabernacle. The people also \"danced\" and broken loose, with connotations of sexual immorality, to the point where they became a disgrace even to \"their enemies\" (32:25)."}, {"prompt": "Read Exodus 32:10; 25-35.  What should have been the judgement on Israel for their sin? What was the actual judgement? What does the actual judgement reveal about God's relationship with Israel now?", "hint": "For the proper judgement of Israel, see 32:10; and recall Gen 15:8-21 - the price to pay for breaking a covenant. \nFor the actual judgement - See v27-28; v35.\nFor God's relationship with Israel now, see 32:34-35, and God's language in 32:7;", "answer": "\"Should\" judgement : Israel, who agreed and entered into covenantal relationship with God through Moses' sprinkling of the blood of the covenant, should have been punished by death, as per what God wanted initially in 32:10. \nActual judgement: Moses, in hot anger, led the Levites to kill the Israelites - 3000 fell. Furthermore, God sent a PLAGUE on the people, because of the people's sin, Aaron's sin. God calls Israel \"your people\" in 32:7;33:1 when speaking to Moses, instead of being His people. These show that God judged Israel similarly to Egypt in the plagues, and the covenant seems broken from how He related to Israel."}, {"prompt": "Moses' intercessions - Read Exodus 32:10-14 & 30-34. What reasons does Moses give in interceding for Israel these two times? What does God's eventual decision reveal about Himself?", "hint": "In both intercessions, Moses appeals to different things in interceding - 32:12-13; 32:30-32.\nCompare God's supposed judgement with his actual judgement also.", "answer": "In the first intercession, Moses appeals to God's name and promises made to Abraham, Isaac and Jacob (32:12-13).\nAfter executing judgement on Israel, Moses tries to make \"atonement\" for Israel's sins, and even identifies with sinful Israel (32:32) in appealing to God for mercy.\nGod shows His holiness through judgement, but shows His mercy in listening to the mediator Moses, and executing partial judgement instead of fully wiping Israel out (except Moses)."}], "summary": "God shows mercy, through Moses, towards a deeply sinful, covenant-breaking Israel.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 33", "title": "Moses' Intercessions", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 33:1-4; 12-17. God initially wanted to not go with Israel to the promised land- a \"disastrous word\" (33:4). Moses intercedes yet again in 33:12-17. How does Moses go about interceding for Israel this time?", "hint": "Exodus 33:12-13 - Moses' appeal to God.", "answer": "Moses appeals to the fact that he has \"found favor\" in God's sight, to \"know\" God and His ways, in order that he may find more favor in God's sight. \nHe emphasises God's presence is what makes Israel distinct (33:16)."}], "summary": "God shows mercy, through the favoured mediator Moses, towards a deeply sinful, covenant-breaking Israel.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Exodus 34", "title": "Covenant Renewal", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Exodus 33:18-19; 34:1-10. God reveals His glory- all His goodness - His name; His character here in 34:6-7. \n(IMPORTANT) God's character will significantly explain/drive the rest of the Old Testament narrative, pointing to Jesus. \n\nWhat do you learn about God's name in 34:6-7?", "hint": "There are 2 main parts of His name. Note \"thousands\" in the ESV has a footnote- \"or the thousandth generation\", to be compared with v7's \"third and fourth\" generation.", "answer": "God's name has 2 big parts. Firstly, His mercy and grace - keeping steadfast love to thousands (or THOUSANDTH generation); forgiving iniquity and sin. \nYet, the second part, talks about His justice- by no means clear the guilty, visiting the iniquity… to the THIRD and FOURTH generation. \nThe contrast between the number of generations highlights God being far more merciful comparatively..."}, {"prompt": "Read Exodus 34:10. How does God's name (Justice, and great mercy) broadly explain all that happened in Exodus 32-34?", "hint": "Where do you see God's justice, and great mercy in Ex 32-34? Exodus 34:10 happens after the golden calf incident.", "answer": "God's justice is demonstrated in how He dealt with sinful Israel, partially through Moses executing His judgement through the Levites, in addition to God's plagues. \nGod's mercy is demonstrated in how He only delivered partial judgement (through Moses) to a sinful Israel deserving death. \nFurthermore, God says he is making covenant like never before - an awesome thing that He will do, despite Israel's sinfulness."}], "summary": "God reveals His name/glory - justice and great mercy, which explains/drives how He relates to a sinful Israel, through favoured Moses. God mercifully renews the covenant after all that happened.", "summaryHint": ""}], "10": [{"range": "Leviticus 16:3-10", "title": "Prep and Overview", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Leviticus 10:1-3 to understand Leviticus 16:1-2. What are the problems Aaron faces when approaching God here? How would Aaron be feeling now?", "hint": "His sons likely got burnt alive in front of him. The whole Israel is watching him during this day. Recall Aaron's role in the golden calf too.", "answer": "Aaron and his family have very recently been shown to be lacking. God chose the high priest to be in charge of making atonement for all of Israel's iniquities. The tone now is one of intense gravity and stress, due to what is at stake and past failures."}, {"prompt": "Read Leviticus 16:3-10. \nNotice how v6 is exactly the same as v11 - indicating that both v6 and v11 marks the start of a section. \n\nV3-10 is very likely an overview/recipe of what happens in the Day of Atonement, with v11 being the start of the next section: details of the ceremony (since v11 would correspond to the identical v6 - i.e. v11-22 being an elaborate breakdown of v6-10). \n\nHow would Aaron need to prepare to approach God based on v2-5, to \"not die\"?", "hint": "Note the offerings and garment changing.", "answer": "To \"not die\", Aaron would need to prepare by bringing sacrifices for himself and being clean. \nHe needs to go into the Holy Place with a sin and burnt offering. He needs to put on the holy linen clothes after bathing."}, {"prompt": "Read Lev 16:5 - What is the difference between sin offerings and burnt offerings? (Leviticus 1- Burnt Offerings; Leviticus 4 - Sin Offerings)\nClick \"Reveal Suggested Answer\" for a quick summary.", "hint": "", "answer": "Sin offerings: Mandatory as part of cleansing and redemption of self (atonement for unintentional sin)\nR/s between God and Man: Broken to Neutral\n\nBurnt offerings: Voluntary, usually offered to praise God or give thanks to Him\nR/s between God and Man: Neutral to Good (Pleasing aroma to God)"}], "summary": "God designs the Day of Atonement for Israel to atone for sin through the perfect, clean high priest and be in right relationship with Him. There is great doubt whether Aaron and his family  can fulfill this role of the clean high priest.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Leviticus 16:11-28", "title": "Offering for Aaron & his house (11-14); Offering for the People (15-22); Post-offering cleansing (22-28)", "questions": [{"prompt": "Read Leviticus 16:11-22. We see offerings made by Aaron for the people of Israel, himself and... What does Aaron atone for?", "hint": "Keep track of who Aaron atones for and how. E.g He starts with atoning for him and his house (v11), then…", "answer": "Aaron starts with atoning for him and his house (v11), then starts atoning for the people (sin offering- unintentional sin) (v15) and starts atoning for… the Holy Place?(V16) This shows the pervasiveness of sin, infecting the Holy Place by proximity to it, that it needs atoning for. Then, Aaron presents the live goat, putting ALL the iniquities of the people of Israel (intentional sin) on the goat before sending it away."}, {"prompt": "After knowing this whole process, Try it yourself! Note  how many lives you lose and how tedious it is :( \nClick \"Hint\" for the photo of the tabernacle.", "hint": "(*Attach Photo of Tabernacle here*)", "answer": "Not only is it really difficult to complete perfectly, and that the high priest's character may be called into question, the stakes are extremely high- all of Israel's relationship with a holy God.", "__IMG__": "imgTabernaclePhoto", "imageAlt": "Photo / diagram of the Tabernacle"}], "summary": "God intends for the tedious Day of Atonement to be done perfectly by a perfectly clean high priest to allow Israel to be clean from their sins.", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Leviticus 16:29-34", "title": "Statute forever", "questions": [{"prompt": "The Day of Atonement had to be done once a year, \"forever\" (16:34). How would you feel as an Israelite throughout the day, across the years?", "hint": "What does the yearly Day of Atonement tell you about the effect of the past Day of Atonements?", "answer": "The requirement for this day of Atonement to be done yearly, \"forever\" shows the inadequacy of the previous day of Atonement in dealing completely with Israel's sins. Furthermore, Israel would likely be in great stress watching their high priest perform the tedious ritual every year."}], "summary": "God intends for the tedious Day of Atonement to be done yearly \"forever\", pointing to the need for a better solution.", "summaryHint": ""}], "11": [{"range": "Deuteronomy 28", "title": "Blessings and Curses", "questions": [{"prompt": "What is the overall pattern of the blessings and curses? (Look at Deuteronomy 28:1 and 28:15).", "hint": "", "answer": "If you faithfully obey the voice of the LORD, being careful to do his commandments, then the blessings shall overtake you. \nIf you will not obey the voice of the LORD or be careful to do ALL his commandments, then all these curses shall overtake you."}, {"prompt": "Recall God's promises to Abraham in Genesis 12:1-3, blessings of land, descendents, blessings and relationship with God. Do similar blessings or curses appear here too? \n(Bonus) Comparing Genesis 15:8-21 and Deuteronomy 28:1; 15, What is different regarding man's roles in both passages?", "hint": "Look at Deuteronomy 28:8-9; 11-12; 20-24; 62.\n(Bonus) Think about the conditions to receive the blessings.", "answer": "Land, descendents and relationship with God are all involved in both the blessings and curses.\n(Bonus) God himself seals the covenant in Genesis 15:8-21. In Deuteronomy 28:1, Israel has to obey ALL of God's commandments."}, {"prompt": "There are significantly more curses as compared to blessings. Why do you think this might be the case?", "hint": "Think about what God is trying to show regarding Himself, the people, and the consequences of sin.", "answer": "Through the many curses, God may have wanted to emphasise His holy character and how much He hates sin, also revealing the true, destructive consequences of sin. \nAlso, note how some curses are oddly specific. Later on, it is revealed that the blessings and curses WILL happen to Israel in Deuteronomy 30:1. These curses hold Israel accountable in that they now fully know the consequences of disobedience and still disobey. This shows Israel's deep sinfulness and inability to truly obey God, depending fully on God to intervene in Deuteronomy 30:6."}], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Deuteronomy 29", "title": "Remembering God's works", "questions": [], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}, {"range": "Deuteronomy 30", "title": "Choose life, not death", "questions": [], "summary": "", "summaryHint": ""}]};
